            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "From http://docutils.sourceforge.net/docs/user/rst/quickref.html#inline-markup:\n\n> [double backticks:] Normally rendered as monospaced text. Spaces should be preserved, but line breaks will not be.\n> \n> [single backticks:] The rendering and meaning of interpreted text is domain- or application-dependent.\n\nThe documentation for single backticks also lists program identifiers as an example, but Sphinx provides `:py:class:` and similar syntax for this case. Also, since single backticks have an ambiguous meaing and might be rendered completely different with different parsers, I think that double backticks are more correct in every sense, and i don't think i've ever seen a project which intentionally uses single backticks for this purpose.\n\nI'd welcome a PR which does the opposite though, convert single to double backticks.\n"
